04873nam a22006975i 9780814708941DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147089417 a10.18574/nyu/9780814708934.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547296  a(OCoLC)911497920  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF505.5b.M868 2016 7aFAM0150002bisacsh04a346.730152231 aMurphy, Jane C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDivorced from Reality :bRethinking Family Dispute Resolution /cJana B. Singer, Jane C. Murphy. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFamilies, Law, and Society ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Historical Overview -- t2. The Critique of the Adversary System and the New Paradigm as a Response -- t3. Expanded Courts with Diminished Legal Norms -- t4. The New Vision Meets the New Family -- t5. From Gladiators and Umpires to Problem- Solvers and Managers -- t6. The Influence of Comparative and International Family Law -- t7. Creating a Twenty- First- Century Family Dispute Resolution System -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past thirty years, there has been a dramatic shift in the way the legal system approaches and resolves family disputes. Traditionally, family law dispute resolution was based on an “adversary” system: two parties and their advocates stood before a judge who determined which party was at fault in a divorce and who would be awarded the rights in a custody dispute. Now, many family courts are opting for a “problem-solving” model in which courts attempt to resolve both legal and non-legal issues. At the same time, American families have changed dramatically. Divorce rates have leveled off and begun to drop, while the number of children born and raised outside of marriage has increased sharply. Fathers are more likely to seek an active role in their children’s lives. While this enhanced paternal involvement benefits children, it also increases the likelihood of disputes between parents. As a result, the families who seek legal dispute resolution have become more diverse and their legal situations more complex. In Divorced from Reality, Jane C. Murphy and Jana B. Singer argue that the current "problem solving" model fails to address the realities of today's families. The authors suggest that while today’s dispute resolution regime may represent an improvement over its more adversary predecessor, it is built largely around the model of a divorcing nuclear family with lawyers representing all parties-a model that fits poorly with the realities of today's disputing families. To serve the families it is meant to help, the legal system must adapt and reshape itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDispute resolution (Law)xUnited States. 0aDispute resolution (Law)zUnited States. 0aDomestic relations courtsxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aDomestic relations courtszUnited States. 0aFamily mediationxUnited States. 0aFamily mediationzUnited States. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / Divorce & Separation.2bisacsh1 aSinger, Jana B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831107289960 cprintz978081470893440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814708934.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814708941423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814708941/original  a978-3-11-072899-6  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 20